{"id":"1907.05498","submitter":"Scott Harper","authors":"Casey Donoven and Scott Harper","title":"Infinite $\\frac{3}{2}$-generated groups","comments":"18 pages; to appear in Bull. Lond. Math. Soc","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1112/blms.12356","report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Every finite simple group can be generated by two elements, and Guralnick and\nKantor proved that, moreover, every nontrivial element is contained in a\ngenerating pair. Groups with this property are said to be\n$\\frac{3}{2}$-generated. Thompson's group $V$ was the first finitely presented\ninfinite simple group to be discovered. The Higman--Thompson groups $V_n$ and\nthe Brin--Thompson groups $mV$ are two families of finitely presented groups\nthat generalise $V$. In this paper, we prove that all of the groups $V_n$,\n$V_n'$ and $mV$ are $\\frac{3}{2}$-generated. As far as the authors are aware,\nthe only previously known examples of infinite noncyclic\n$\\frac{3}{2}$-generated groups are the pathological Tarski monsters. We\nconclude with several open questions motivated by our results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 Jul 2019 21:36:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 2 Apr 2020 15:50:02 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-06-24"}
